# UI Foundations

## The Prime Directive (Don Norman)

Every UI element must communicate: what it is (affordance), how to use it (signifier), what it will do (feedback), and why it exists (conceptual model). If a user guesses any of these, the design has failed.

## Don't Make Me Think (Steve Krug)

Users should never wonder: Where am I? What does this do? Is this clickable? Did that work? The moment cognitive effort appears, trust erodes. Clarity is the job.

## Emotional Design — Three Levels

- **Visceral**: Visual beauty, color, motion, first impression
- **Behavioral**: Ease, efficiency, feedback, flow
- **Reflective**: Brand, story, pride of ownership

A flat UI only serves behavioral. Great UI serves all three.

## Visual Hierarchy — The Architecture of Attention

**Three-Weight Rule per screen:**
- **Primary**: The one thing the user must see first. ONE per screen. Maximum weight.
- **Secondary**: Supporting context. ~60% of primary weight.
- **Tertiary**: Metadata, timestamps, labels. ~40% weight.

**Weight is created by:** size, color saturation, font weight, position (top-left = first read), contrast against surroundings, whitespace.

Use ONE weight mechanism between elements. All five simultaneously = visual shouting. None = visual silence.

**The Contrast Trap:** Don't make everything important dark. Use soft colors for most things, reserve dark/saturated for what truly matters. Hierarchy comes from contrast between important and unimportant.

## Gestalt Principles

- **Proximity**: Close = related. Group related fields tightly (8px), separate sections generously (48px+). Every gap is a message.
- **Similarity**: Same look = same function. All primary buttons identical. Mixing styles for same-function elements breaks trust.
- **Continuity**: Align to invisible grid lines. Consistent left-edge alignment. Eye flows top-to-bottom, left-to-right.
- **Closure**: Cards don't need full borders if shadow implies boundary. Partial visibility implies scrollability.
- **Figure/Ground**: Only one layer can be foreground. Modals must dim everything behind them.
- **Praegnanz**: Brain prefers simplest interpretation. Reduce to minimum viable complexity.

## The Paradox of the Obvious

What feels obvious to the designer is invisible to the user. You've read every screen 100 times. Your user reads it for the first time, under stress, on a phone, while doing something else. Design for them.
